Step 1. Free Cash Flow (FCF)
• From the cash‐flow statement, we add Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities and Net Cash Flow from Investing Activities. 
  Operating CF = –64,099.10 
  Investing CF = –528,936.17 
  FCF = –64,099.10 + (–528,936.17) = –593,035.27

Step 2. Return on Assets (ROA)
• ROA is calculated as Net Profit divided by the average Total Assets.
  Beginning Total Assets = 13,000,000.00 
  Ending Total Assets = 15,200,446.16 
  Average Total Assets = (13,000,000.00 + 15,200,446.16) / 2 = 14,100,223.08 
  Net Profit = 707,199.17 
  ROA = (707,199.17 / 14,100,223.08) × 100 ≈ 5.02%

Step 3. Return on Equity (ROE)
• ROE is calculated as Net Profit divided by the average Owner’s Equity.
  Beginning Owner’s Equity = 13,000,000.00 
  Ending Owner’s Equity = 13,707,199.17 
  Average Owner’s Equity = (13,000,000.00 + 13,707,199.17) / 2 = 13,353,599.59 
  ROE = (707,199.17 / 13,353,599.59) × 100 ≈ 5.30%

Step 4. Operating Cash Flow to Net Income Ratio
• This ratio is calculated as Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities divided by Net Profit.
  = (–64,099.10 / 707,199.17) ≈ –0.09

Step 5. Net Profit Margin
• Net Profit Margin is found by dividing Net Profit by Total Revenue.
  Total Revenue = 5,064,939.23 
  = (707,199.17 / 5,064,939.23) × 100 ≈ 13.96%

Step 6. Gross Profit Margin
• Gross Profit Margin is calculated as Gross Profit divided by Total Revenue.
  Gross Profit = 2,329,939.23 
  = (2,329,939.23 / 5,064,939.23) × 100 ≈ 46.00%

Based on these calculations, the final results are:

    "Return on Assets (ROA)": "5.02%",
    "Return on Equity (ROE)": "5.30%",
    "Operating Cash Flow to Net Income Ratio": "-0.09",
    "Net Profit Margin": "13.96%",
    "Gross Profit Margin": "46.00%"
  }
}
